  "title": "Spectra - could 18 eV photon interact with gs atom",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an energy level diagram of an atom. The diagram has five levels labeled, from top to bottom, 0 electron volts, negative 1 electron volt, negative 4 electron volts, negative 7 electron volts, and negative 14 electron volts. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"/images/25a6abc09c21e041b3bbcb17bbde8b21.svg\"></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The diagram shows the energy levels of a hypothetical atom. The energy state at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"0 electron volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0</mn><mspace width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></math></span></span> corresponds to an ionized atom, and the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative 14 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"negative 14 electron volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>−</mo><mn>14</mn><mspace width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></math></span></span> state is the atom’s ground state. For an atom in the ground state, could a photon of energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"18 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"18 electron volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>18</mn><mspace width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></math></span></span> interact with the atom? What reasoning supports the answer?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i1",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The photon’s energy is greater than the atom’s binding energy.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. There are two energy states with energies that sum to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative 18 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"negative 18 electron volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>−</mo><mn>18</mn><mspace width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i2"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. An atom in its lowest-energy state cannot interact with photons.</p>",
        "value": "i3"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. There is no energy difference between any two states that is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"18 electron volts\"><math alttext=\"18 electron volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>18</mn><mspace width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i4"
      }
    ]
  },
